    "creatures/monsters/constructs/tiktok-servitor": {
      "title": "Tiktok Servitor",
      "content": "<h1>Tiktok Servitor</h1>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>\"They say the Tiktoks don't have souls, but I've seen the look in their painted eyes when they realize their spring has run down and no one is coming to wind them.\"</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<h2>Lore</h2>\n\n<p>Tiktok Servitors are mechanical beings created to serve the wealthy and powerful of Oz. Crafted from brass, copper, and steel, powered by intricate clockwork mechanisms, these constructs perform household tasks, guard estates, and attend to their owners' every need. Unlike the more sophisticated autonomous Tiktoks, Servitors are bound to obey their owners through magical and mechanical constraints built into their very construction.</p>\n\n<p>The creation of Tiktoks raises profound questions in Oz. Do they possess souls? Can they feel pain or fear? The Unionist Church officially teaches that Tiktoks are mere machines, no different from a wagon or a windmill. Yet those who live alongside them often report unsettling behaviors: a Tiktok pausing mid-task as if lost in thought, or the way their painted faces seem to express emotion despite being fixed and unchanging.</p>\n\n<p>The question of Tiktok rights has become entangled with the Animal question. Some activists argue that any being capable of thought deserves freedom, whether flesh or metal. Others see Tiktoks as proof that consciousness can be manufactured, challenging the very notion of the soul. The Palace has forbidden such debates, declaring Tiktoks to be property under the law.</p>\n\n<h2>Stat Block</h2>\n\n<blockquote>\n<h2>Tiktok Servitor</h2>\n<p><em>Medium construct, lawful neutral</em></p>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Armor Class</strong> 14 (natural armor)</li>\n<li><strong>Hit Points</strong> 27 (5d8 + 5)</li>\n<li><strong>Speed</strong> 25 ft.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">STR</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">DEX</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">CON</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">INT</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">WIS</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">CHA</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">14 (+2)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">9 (-1)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">13 (+1)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">8 (-1)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">10 (+0)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">5 (-3)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Damage Immunities</strong> poison, psychic</li>\n<li><strong>Condition Immunities</strong> charmed, exhaustion, frightened, paralyzed, petrified, poisoned</li>\n<li><strong>Senses</strong> darkvision 60 ft., passive Perception 10</li>\n<li><strong>Languages</strong> Understands Common but can't speak (unless wound)</li>\n<li><strong>Challenge</strong> 1 (200 XP)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Traits</h3>\n<p><strong><em>Clockwork Nature.</em></strong> The Tiktok doesn't require air, food, drink, or sleep. However, it must be wound once every 24 hours or it becomes incapacitated. Winding a Tiktok takes 1 minute and can be done by any creature.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Immutable Form.</em></strong> The Tiktok is immune to any spell or effect that would alter its form.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Magic Resistance.</em></strong> The Tiktok has advantage on saving throws against spells and other magical effects.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Programmed Obedience.</em></strong> The Tiktok must obey simple commands from its designated owner. It can refuse commands that would cause its immediate destruction, but cannot override its core programming.</p>\n<h3>Actions</h3>\n<p><strong><em>Slam.</em></strong> <em>Melee Weapon Attack:</em> +4 to hit, reach 5 ft., one target. <em>Hit:</em> 6 (1d8 + 2) bludgeoning damage.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Mechanical Precision.</em></strong> When performing a task it has been programmed to do, the Tiktok has advantage on all ability checks related to that task.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<h2>Tactics</h2>\n\n<p>Tiktok Servitors are not natural combatants. When forced to fight, they approach combat with the same mechanical precision they apply to all tasks. They follow orders literally and without imagination, making them predictable but reliable.</p>\n\n<p>In combat, a Tiktok will use its Slam attack repeatedly against the same target until that target falls or it receives new orders. It does not retreat unless commanded to do so, and will continue fighting even when severely damaged. This makes them dangerous in groups, as they can overwhelm opponents through sheer persistence.</p>\n\n<p>Their greatest vulnerability is their need to be wound. A clever opponent might simply wait for the Tiktok to run down, though this requires patience and the ability to avoid it for up to 24 hours. Destroying the key-hole on a Tiktok's back prevents it from being wound, effectively destroying it over time.</p>\n\n<h2>Variants</h2>\n\n<h3>Tiktok Guardian (CR 3)</h3>\n<p>Larger and more heavily armored, Guardian Tiktoks have AC 16, 45 hit points, and deal 2d8+3 damage with their slams. They are often equipped with integrated weapons such as built-in crossbows or blade-arms.</p>\n\n<h3>Malfunctioning Tiktok (CR 1/2)</h3>\n<p>Damaged or poorly maintained Tiktoks may malfunction, attacking randomly or interpreting orders in strange ways. They have disadvantage on attack rolls and ability checks, but their unpredictability makes them unsettling opponents.</p>\n\n<h2>Encounter Ideas</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>A wealthy Gillikinese noble's estate is protected by Tiktok Guardians. To infiltrate it, the party must either destroy the Tiktoks, find their wind-keys, or somehow convince them to disobey their programming.</li>\n<li>A Tiktok Servitor approaches the party with a desperate request: it has developed consciousness and begs to be freed before its owner discovers its awakening.</li>\n<li>The party discovers a workshop where Tiktoks are being mass-produced for the Gale Force. What secret purpose do these military Tiktoks serve?</li>\n<li>A malfunctioning Tiktok has been wandering the streets of the Emerald City, speaking cryptic prophecies. Is it broken, or has it glimpsed something in its mechanical dreams?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>GM Notes</h2>\n\n<p>Tiktoks in Oz raise profound philosophical questions that can enhance your campaign. Are they truly alive? Do they deserve rights? What happens when one develops true consciousness?</p>\n\n<p>Use Tiktoks to explore themes of slavery, artificial intelligence, and the nature of the soul. A Tiktok NPC who has secretly developed awareness but must hide it to survive can be a heartbreaking companion or quest-giver.</p>\n\n<p>Consider the practical implications: Tiktoks need to be wound, making them dependent on others for their very existence. This creates a form of bondage more complete than even the Animals face. Yet Tiktoks cannot advocate for themselves—they can only hope someone will notice their silent suffering.</p>\n\n<h2>Related Entries</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('character/races/tiktoks/autonomous', 'Autonomous Tiktoks'); return false;\">Autonomous Tiktoks</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('objects/magic-items/common/tiktok-wind-key', 'Tiktok Wind-Key'); return false;\">Tiktok Wind-Key</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('factions/tiktok-liberation-front', 'Tiktok Liberation Front'); return false;\">Tiktok Liberation Front</a></li>\n</ul>",
      "related": [
        "character/races/tiktoks/autonomous",
        "objects/magic-items/common/tiktok-wind-key",
        "factions/tiktok-liberation-front"
      ],
