    "npcs/elphaba-thropp": {
      "title": "Elphaba Thropp",
      "content": "<h1>Elphaba Thropp</h1>\n\n<p><em>Munchkinlander Human, Adept (Reader) 18, Chaotic Good (or Neutral Good, or just Chaotic)</em></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>\"I'm wicked through and through, they say. But I've never made someone disappear who didn't threaten Animals first. I've never tortured confessions or drained marshes or Silenced anyone. So who, exactly, is wicked?\"</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<h2>At a Glance</h2>\n\n<p><strong>Role:</strong> Revolutionary, Witch, Symbol of Resistance (depending on era and perspective)</p>\n<p><strong>Location:</strong> Kiamo Ko (in later life), various locations during her activist years, deceased by the time of most campaigns (but her legacy endures)</p>\n<p><strong>Attitude:</strong> Hostile to authority, protective of the oppressed, deeply distrustful but capable of fierce loyalty to those she loves</p>\n\n<h2>Appearance</h2>\n\n<p>Elphaba's most striking feature is her green skin—a deep emerald that caused her mother to scream when she was born. Her eyes are dark and intense, her hair black and wild. She is tall and angular, with sharp features that some find harsh and others find compelling. In her youth, she dressed practically, favoring dark colors that didn't show dirt. Later, she embraced the pointed hat and dramatic black clothing that people expected from the \"Wicked Witch.\"</p>\n\n<p>She moves with purpose and energy, often seeming to take up more space than her physical form suggests. When angry or casting magic, her green skin seems to darken and her eyes flash. In rare moments of peace, her face softens, revealing the person she might have been in a kinder world.</p>\n\n<p>She has an aversion to water—it pains her skin, making bathing difficult and rain miserable. This has contributed to her reputation for uncleanliness, though in truth she's meticulous about hygiene within the limits her condition allows.</p>\n\n<h2>Personality</h2>\n\n<p>Elphaba is brilliant, passionate, and profoundly angry at injustice. She cannot look away from suffering, even when doing so would be easier or safer. This moral clarity is both her greatest strength and her fatal flaw—she will sacrifice anything, including herself, for what she believes is right.</p>\n\n<p>She is not easy to like. She's prickly, judgmental, and often fails to understand social niceties. She says what she thinks without cushioning it, and she has little patience for those who prioritize comfort over justice. Yet those who earn her trust discover a fierce friend capable of great tenderness, particularly toward Animals, children, and the marginalized.</p>\n\n<p>Her relationship with power is complex. She craves the ability to change things, but she despises authority and those who wield it selfishly. The Grimmerie offers her tremendous power, but reading it is slowly destroying her. She knows this and does it anyway, because what else can she do in the face of such overwhelming evil?</p>\n\n<p>Underneath the anger is tremendous pain. She's lonely, convinced she's unlovable because of her green skin. She's mourning—for Dr. Dillamond, for Fiyero, for all the Animals who've suffered, for the person she might have been. She's also consumed by guilt over the things she's done, the people she's hurt, the moral lines she's crossed.</p>\n\n<h2>Background</h2>\n\n<p>Born to Frex, a Unionist minister, and Melena Thropp in Munchkinland's Rush Margins, Elphaba's green skin marked her as different from birth. Her father saw her as punishment for his wife's sins. Her mother drowned her sorrows in wine and fantasy. Only her nanny, Nanny, showed her affection.</p>\n\n<p>At Shiz University, Elphaba studied sorcery under Madame Morrible while pursuing a degree in life sciences. She befriended (and was changed by) Dr. Dillamond, a Goat professor whose research into Animal consciousness was deemed dangerous by the authorities. His murder radicalized her, setting her on a path of resistance against the Wizard's regime.</p>\n\n<p>Her complicated relationship with Glinda Upland—roommate, friend, rival, and perhaps something more—shaped both their lives. Where Elphaba chose resistance, Glinda chose accommodation, becoming \"Glinda the Good\" and working within the system. Their divergent paths haunt them both.</p>\n\n<p>Elphaba's affair with Fiyero, an Arjiki prince, gave her one of the few genuine connections of her life. His apparent death devastated her, though rumors persist that she saved him through magic at a terrible cost.</p>\n\n<p>In her later years, she retreated to Kiamo Ko in the Vinkus, raising Fiyero's children and studying the Grimmerie. She became the Wicked Witch of the West in truth, though whether she was wicked or simply desperate remains a matter of perspective. Her apparent death at Dorothy Gale's hands became myth, but like everything about Elphaba, the truth is more complicated.</p>\n\n<h2>Goals & Motivations</h2>\n\n<p><strong>Current Goals:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Protect Animals from persecution and restore their rights</li>\n<li>Understand and master the Grimmerie's magic, despite the cost</li>\n<li>Undermine the Wizard's (later the Emperor's) authority</li>\n<li>Keep those she loves safe, even if it means pushing them away</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Long-term Ambitions:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Overthrow the corrupt government and establish a just society</li>\n<li>Uncover the truth about Oz's history and the sources of magic</li>\n<li>Prove that she is not wicked, or at least that wickedness is more complex than good and evil</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Fears:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Failure—that all her sacrifices will accomplish nothing</li>\n<li>That she really is wicked, that power has corrupted her as it corrupts everyone</li>\n<li>Water, which burns her skin</li>\n<li>Losing those few people she loves</li>\n<li>That the Grimmerie will consume her before she can finish her work</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Roleplaying Elphaba Thropp</h2>\n\n<p><strong>Voice & Manner:</strong> Sharp, precise, often sarcastic. She speaks quickly when passionate, which is often. Her voice can be harsh, but it can also be gentle with those she trusts. She has a tendency to lecture when she feels strongly about something.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Quirks:</strong> Avoids water compulsively. Touches her hat when nervous. Quotes Dr. Dillamond frequently. Has a nervous habit of checking that her spellbook is still in her bag.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Key Phrases:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"Because I cannot do good, must I therefore do nothing?\"</li>\n<li>\"They call me wicked. Fine. I'll be wicked on my own terms.\"</li>\n<li>\"Dr. Dillamond used to say...\"</li>\n<li>\"You don't understand what they're doing to Animals out there!\"</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Interaction Tips:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>She responds well to directness and poorly to flattery</li>\n<li>Mention Animal rights positively and you'll have her attention</li>\n<li>She respects competence and commitment over charm</li>\n<li>Don't mention her green skin unless you want an icy response</li>\n<li>Show her evidence of injustice and she'll feel compelled to act</li>\n<li>She's more vulnerable than she appears—kindness catches her off-guard</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stats (if needed for combat)</h2>\n\n<blockquote>\n<h2>Elphaba Thropp</h2>\n<p><em>Medium humanoid (human), chaotic good</em></p>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Armor Class</strong> 15 (Mage Armor)</li>\n<li><strong>Hit Points</strong> 99 (18d6 + 36)</li>\n<li><strong>Speed</strong> 30 ft., fly 60 ft. (broom)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">STR</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">DEX</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">CON</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">INT</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">WIS</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center\">CHA</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">10 (+0)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">14 (+2)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">14 (+2)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">20 (+5)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">16 (+3)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center\">12 (+1)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Saving Throws</strong> Int +11, Wis +9</li>\n<li><strong>Skills</strong> Arcana +11, History +11, Investigation +11, Insight +9, Perception +9</li>\n<li><strong>Damage Vulnerabilities</strong> Water deals double damage (unique vulnerability)</li>\n<li><strong>Damage Resistances</strong> Necrotic</li>\n<li><strong>Senses</strong> Passive Perception 19</li>\n<li><strong>Languages</strong> Common (Ozian), Qua'ati (Quadling), Vinkus dialect, Grimmerie script</li>\n<li><strong>Challenge</strong> 13 (10,000 XP)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Traits</h3>\n<p><strong><em>Spellcasting.</em></strong> Elphaba is an 18th-level spellcaster. Her spellcasting ability is Intelligence (spell save DC 19, +11 to hit with spell attacks). She has the following Adept spells prepared:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cantrips (at will): <em>Green-Light, Mage Hand, Prestidigitation, Ray of Frost</em></li>\n<li>1st level (4 slots): <em>Detect Magic, Mage Armor, Magic Missile, Shield</em></li>\n<li>2nd level (3 slots): <em>Levitate, Memory Jar, Invisibility</em></li>\n<li>3rd level (3 slots): <em>Counterspell, Fly, Dispel Magic</em></li>\n<li>4th level (3 slots): <em>Polymorph, Greater Invisibility, Banishment</em></li>\n<li>5th level (3 slots): <em>Telekinesis, Wall of Force, Dominate Person</em></li>\n<li>6th level (1 slot): <em>Globe of Invulnerability, Chain Lightning</em></li>\n<li>7th level (1 slot): <em>Reverse Gravity, Teleport</em></li>\n<li>8th level (1 slot): <em>Demiplane, Power Word Stun</em></li>\n<li>9th level (1 slot): <em>Time Stop, Wish (extremely rare, dangerous)</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong><em>Grimmerie Corruption.</em></strong> Elphaba has read deeply from the Grimmerie. She can cast any spell she knows at one level higher without using a higher-level slot, but when she does, she takes 1d6 necrotic damage per spell level. This damage cannot be reduced or prevented.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Water Vulnerability.</em></strong> Contact with water deals 1d4 acid damage per round to Elphaba. Full immersion would be lethal. She cannot swim and avoids rain when possible.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Witch-Mark.</em></strong> Elphaba's green skin makes her instantly recognizable and grants her advantage on Intimidation checks against those who fear magic, but disadvantage on Persuasion checks with most people.</p>\n<h3>Actions</h3>\n<p><strong><em>Grimmerie Blast.</em></strong> <em>Ranged Spell Attack:</em> +11 to hit, range 120 ft., one target. <em>Hit:</em> 28 (4d10 + 5) force damage.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Flying Monkeys.</em></strong> Once per day, if Elphaba possesses the Golden Cap, she can summon 2d6 flying monkeys to serve her for one hour.</p>\n<h3>Reactions</h3>\n<p><strong><em>Shield.</em></strong> When hit by an attack, Elphaba can cast <em>Shield</em> as a reaction, increasing her AC by 5 until the start of her next turn.</p>\n<p><strong><em>Counterspell.</em></strong> When a creature within 60 feet casts a spell, Elphaba can attempt to counter it.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<h2>Quest Hooks</h2>\n\n<p><strong>Quests She Might Offer:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>\"I need you to smuggle this family of Animal refugees to safety. The Gale Force is hunting them, and I can't be seen helping—it would endanger too many others.\"</li>\n<li>\"There's a Grimmerie fragment in the Emerald City archives. Get it for me before it falls into the wrong hands. I'll teach you a spell in exchange.\"</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><strong>Quests Involving Her:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>The party is hired to hunt \"the Wicked Witch of the West.\" When they find her, they discover she's protecting Animal orphans from the Gale Force. What do they do?</li>\n<li>Elphaba appears to the party in a time of crisis, offering help—but accepting it means making an enemy of the government. Her aid comes with consequences.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2>Relationships</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Glinda Upland:</strong> Former roommate and complicated friend. They haven't spoken in years, but each thinks of the other often. Love, resentment, regret, and understanding all tangled together.</li>\n<li><strong>Fiyero:</strong> Her great love, whose fate is uncertain. She either mourns him or has saved him in a way that makes their relationship impossible.</li>\n<li><strong>The Wizard/Emperor Shell:</strong> Her enemy, the embodiment of corrupt authority</li>\n<li><strong>Dr. Dillamond:</strong> Dead mentor whose murder set her on this path. She carries his watch.</li>\n<li><strong>Madame Morrible:</strong> Former teacher turned enemy, manipulator who used her</li>\n<li><strong>Nessarose (sister):</strong> Complicated relationship, guilt over her sister's fate</li>\n<li><strong>Animal Resistance:</strong> Ally and sometimes leader, though she works mostly alone</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>GM Notes</h2>\n\n<p>Elphaba is one of Oz's most significant figures, but use her carefully. She can overshadow player characters if overused. Consider these approaches:</p>\n\n<p><strong>As Legend:</strong> She's already dead by the campaign's start, but her legacy shapes everything. The party encounters people she saved, those she hurt, places she marked, and the ongoing consequences of her choices.</p>\n\n<p><strong>As Distant Ally:</strong> She helps the party indirectly—leaving information, creating diversions, sending messages through intermediaries. They know she exists but rarely meet her.</p>\n\n<p><strong>As Moral Center:</strong> The party encounters her once or twice at crucial moments. She challenges their assumptions, asks difficult questions, and forces them to consider what they're willing to sacrifice for justice.</p>\n\n<p><strong>As Antagonist:</strong> If your campaign is from the government's perspective or explores moral ambiguity, Elphaba can be an opponent. She's not evil, but her methods are extreme, and her attacks on government facilities endanger innocent people.</p>\n\n<p>Remember that Elphaba is a person, not a symbol. She makes mistakes, hurts people she loves, and sometimes chooses poorly. She's consumed by her cause in ways that aren't always healthy. She can be wrong. This complexity makes her compelling.</p>\n\n<h2>Related Entries</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('character/classes/the-adept', 'The Adept'); return false;\">The Adept</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('exploration/locations/kiamo-ko', 'Kiamo Ko'); return false;\">Kiamo Ko</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('objects/magic-items/legendary/the-grimmerie', 'The Grimmerie'); return false;\">The Grimmerie</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('npcs/glinda-upland', 'Glinda Upland'); return false;\">Glinda Upland</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"Tabs.openTab('factions/animal-resistance', 'Animal Resistance'); return false;\">Animal Resistance</a></li>\n</ul>",
